## Summary

**9 of 10 tests** suffer from the "call-it-and-pray" anti-pattern — they touch production code (driving coverage) but verify nothing meaningful. The 3 `IsNotNull` assertions are only marginally better: they confirm a return value exists but never check correctness. This is why bugs escape to production despite 95% coverage. **Coverage measures lines executed, not behavior verified.**
